{"source_key":"sha256-030eed7c2b37e7a052500d0b6a51d640","record_index":335,"record_hash":"sha256:f11e2dbd6112d18cb85b61334109c634654a5226195863b94ae366bdf43e4da3","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:05:12.742Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 58d9cf\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 3370\nOutput:\n  dependency graph is too heavy\n\nExample shape:\n\n```toml\nbut-agentlog = { git = \"https://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\", rev = \"<pinned-revision>\", package = \"but-agentlog\" }\n```\n\nThe important rule is no copied reader logic. Forge may own Agent Trail\npublication and UI policy, but the canonical storage interpretation should stay\nin `but-agentlog`.\n\nBuild may start for public repos and publicly fetchable metadata. Private repo,\nteam, explicit-share, and richer publication flows are later work.\n\n## Server-Side Metadata Fetch\n\nFor public v1, the Forge server should be able to create an Agent Trail snapshot\non demand by fetching GitMeta metadata for the repository referenced by the PR\nURL.\n\nExample local setup:\n\n```ini\n[remote \"meta\"]\n  url = git@github.com:gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\n  fetch = +refs/meta/main:refs/meta/remote/main\n  meta = true\n  promisor = true\n  partialclonefilter = blob:none\n```\n\nThe server should not assume it can see a developer's local Git remote config.\nGiven a URL like:\n\n```text\nhttps://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler/pull/13936\n```\n\nthe server should resolve the public GitHub repository, then fetch\n`refs/meta/main` from that same public repository.\n\nPossible first flow:\n\n1. parse the PR URL into forge, owner, repo, and PR number\n2. fetch GitHub PR metadata and verify that the repository and pull request are\n   public/readable\n3. reject fork pull requests for v1\n4. create or refresh a server-side bare/cache checkout for the repository\n5. fetch `refs/meta/main`\n6. resolve the fetched metadata ref to an OID\n7. run `but-agentlog` lookup/projection code against\n   the fetched repository metadata\n8. generate a review-safe Agent Trail snapshot\n9. cache or return that snapshot according to the retention policy\n\nThe server can lazy-initialize repository storage. On the first request for a\nrepository, initialize a bare/cache checkout. On later requests,\nreuse the cached repository\n[TRUNCATED]\nhese `but-agentlog` guarantees:\n\n- records must be redacted\n- local filesystem paths should not be exposed\n- raw provider session ids should not be exposed\n- hidden/system/developer prompts should not be exposed\n- source records should stay bounded and redacted\n- the user should understand that the trail may contain prompts and tool output\n\nIf the required `but-agentlog` public/read projection does not exist yet, build\nthat before rendering Agent Trail pages from Forge.\n\nPublic v1 snapshots should be public but not promoted. Serve them with\n`noindex` until the publication model is more mature.\n\n## Permissions\n\nFirst version: public repositories and public metadata only.\n\nThe server may generate or show an Agent Trail only when it can access the PR\nand GitMeta metadata without private credentials. Private repository support\nshould be a later design pass.\n\nFuture policy options:\n\n- GitButler team/workspace members\n- same users who can view the repository\n- same users who can view the pull request\n- explicit share link recipients\n\nFor private repositories, defaulting to repository/PR visibility is probably the\nleast surprising, but do not build that into v1.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- no claim that agent sessions authored the pull request\n- no full transcript dump as the main experience\n- no copying transcript records onto pull request targets\n- no product-specific review payloads inside `but-agentlog`\n- no magic generated summary as the source of truth\n- no private repository support in v1\n- no fork pull request support in v1\n- no GitHub OAuth or GitButler workspace auth in v1\n- no configurable metadata remotes or arbitrary metadata refs in v1\n- no GitHub check-run, GitHub app panel, or PR-comment automation in v1\n- no change-target lookup in v1\n- no user session exclusion/hiding flow in v1\n- no automatic private or team-visible publishing just because capture succeeded\n- no cryptographic audit or compliance story for v1\n\n## Failure States\n\nV1 should distinguish \"we looked and found nothing\" from \"we could not look.\"\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:05:12.742Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}